PSYC800_Unit1Project

Overview

Topic Area: Social Sciences

Specific subtopic: Perception of Choice within Marriage among North Americans vs South Asian Indians

This project extends cultural psychological research on construing actions as choices to the study of relationships. In an experiment, we manipulated perceived choice in marriage and observed its effect on perceived choice present in the arrangement and peopleâs predictions (through their perceptions) about marital well-being, marriage longevity, and familial happiness. This was interesting as we recruited both South Asian Indian and North American sample (Indian N = 109, American N = 102). Participants read a vignette of a family arranging their offspring's marriage in which either the couple chose their marital partners (choice condition) or their family chose their marital partners for them (no-choice condition). Analysis of the differences in peopleâs perceptions of marriage through the lens of their Nationalities was fascinating.

Wrangling

The data source is a study we ran in February 2023. The study was conducted through a Qualtrics survey and the dataset was designed accordingly. It was easy to export the Qualtrics data as an Excel file, check for discrepancies, sort them, and then export the dataset as a CSV. Then the data was imported into R (as below). I chose to import the full dataset and the columns with NA values were not utilized in my analysis for this project. Next, I ran some correlations on the variables that could be grouped together for analysis.

Variables in Wrangled the dataset:

Nationality (categorical): 1 (American), -1 (Indian)

Condition (categorical) : 1(More choice in Marriage), -1 (Less/No choice in Marriage)

Gen (gender, categorical): 0 (Male), 1 (Female)

choice_couple (categorical): Perceived amount of choice the couple had in their marriage (0= No choice, 4= A of choice)

choice_family(categorical): Perceived amount of choice the family had in the coupleâs marriage (0= No choice, 4= A of choice)

I further utilized the correlations above to mutate variables into one variable for overall satisfaction, love, intimacy, and respect in the marriage after 2 years and 10 years respectively. I further filtered them for American nationality oriented participants.

o_satisfaction_2 : Predicted (by participants) overall satisfaction among the couple in the marriage after 2 years

o_love_2: Predicted (by participants) overall love among the couple in the marriage after 2 years

o_intimacy_2: Predicted (by participants) overall intimacy among the couple in the marriage after 2 years

o_respect_2: Predicted (by participants) overall respect among the couple in the marriage after 2 years

(likewise were the variables for predicted (by participants) overall satisfaction, love, intimacy, and respect, among the couple in the marriage after 10 years)

 x<- 
   cm_data |> 
   arrange(desc(ID)) |> 
   mutate(gen = factor(gen, levels = c(0, 1),
                                 labels = c("Male", "Female"))) |> 
   mutate(
          o_satisfaction_2 = satisfaction_2 + happiness_2 + contentment_2,
          o_love_2 = love_2 + friendship_2 + adoration_2,
          o_intimacy_2 = intimacy_2 + closeness_2 + connection_2,
          o_respect_2 = loyalty_2 + respect_2 + understanding_2,
          
          o_satisfaction_10 = satisfaction_10 + happiness_10 + contentment_10,
          o_love_10 = love_10 + friendship_10 + adoration_10,
          o_intimacy_10 = intimacy_10 + closeness_10 + connection_10,
          o_respect_10 = loyalty_10 + respect_10 + understanding_10) |>
   select (Nationality, gen, choice_couple, choice_family, o_satisfaction_2, o_love_2, o_intimacy_2, o_respect_2, o_satisfaction_10, o_love_10, o_intimacy_10, o_respect_10) |> 
   filter(Nationality == 1) |> 
   print()

I first ran a multiple regression with overall satisfaction as the DV and choice among couple and participant gender as the IVs.

Conclusions

From Figures 1 and 2

  • Even when the perceived marital choice among the couple is less or none at all, the American females predict greater marital satisfaction among the couple relative to American males after both 2years and 10 years span.

  • As the perceived marital choice among the couple increases, the American males predict greater overall marital satisfaction among the couple relative to American females in both 2years and 10 years span.

From Figures 3 and 4

  • When Americans perceive that the familial choice in marriage was greater, their predicted level of love in the marriage after 2 years shows a decrease.

  • When Americans perceive that the familial choice in marriage was greater, their predicted level of love in the marriage after 10 years remains stable.

From Figures 5 and 6

  • Predictions of overall respect in marriage in 2 vs 10 years remain greater for Indian females while Indian males predict higher overall respect in marriage after 10 years relative to after 2 years.

Retrospective

About doing data science with real-world data, I learnt that real-world data is often messier, more complex, and less structured. Real-world data sets are large, noisy, and contain numerous missing values and/or outliers. Additionally, real-world data may have data inconsistent data types, or data inaccuracies. Cleaning this data is challenging and requires an understanding of data wrangling techniques.

In contrast, examples from class are usually clean, well-structured, and have been carefully curated to teach specific concepts. Instructors happen to select examples that are more directly focused and easy to work with, so students can focus on learning the underlying principles, tools, and concepts. Examples from class are cleaned and pre-processed before they can be analyzed as opposed to real-world data.

Collecting own data required to firstly have domain-specific knowledge, then plan the data collection process, check ethical considerations, collect data, wrangle data, and further analyse data using specific R functions and codes. Some of the challenges were: it was time consuming to clean data and make it usable for analysis, and learning of relevant data analysis techniques was required.
